      "class": null,
      "title": {
        "segmentId": "m66442:title:fs-id1802099-title",
        "text": "Amino Acids"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "para",
          "id": "fs-id1344438",
          "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id1344438"
        },
        {
          "type": "figure",
          "id": "fig-ch03_04_01",
          "caption": {
            "segmentId": "m66442:caption:fig-ch03_04_01-caption"
          },
          "media": {
            "id": "fs-id1694813",
            "alt": "The molecular structure of an amino acid is given. An amino acid has an alpha carbon to which an amino group, a carboxyl group, a hydrogen, and a side chain are attached. The side chain varies for different amino acids, and is designated as the R - group.",
            "src": "../../media/Figure_03_04_01.png",
            "mimeType": "image/png"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "para",
          "id": "fs-id2941991",
          "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id2941991"
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "fs-id2098380",
          "class": "visual-connection",
          "title": null,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "para",
              "id": "fs-id2051550",
              "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id2051550"
            },
            {
              "type": "para",
              "id": "fs-id1468946",
              "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id1468946"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "figure",
          "id": "fig-ch03_04_02",
          "caption": {
            "segmentId": "m66442:caption:fig-ch03_04_02-caption"
          },
          "media": {
            "id": "fs-id1645231",
            "alt": "The molecular structures of the twenty amino acids commonly found in proteins are given. These are divided into five categories: nonpolar aliphatic, polar uncharged, positively charged, negatively charged, and aromatic. Nonpolar aliphatic amino acids include glycine, alanine, valine, leucine, methionine, isoleucine, and proline. Polar uncharged amino acids include serine, threonine, cysteine, asparagine, and glutamine. Positively charged amino acids include lysine, arginine, and histidine. Negatively charged amino acids include aspartate and glutamate. Aromatic amino acids include phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan.  For example, in the amino acid glycine, the R group is a single hydrogen; but in alanine the R group is upper C upper H subscript 3 baseline.",
            "src": "../../media/Figure_03_04_02-fd30.jpg",
            "mimeType": "image/jpeg"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "para",
          "id": "fs-id1953709",
          "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id1953709"
        },
        {
          "type": "para",
          "id": "fs-id1506615",
          "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id1506615"
        },
        {
          "type": "para",
          "id": "fs-id2235262",
          "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id2235262"
        },
        {
          "type": "figure",
          "id": "fig-ch03_04_03",
          "caption": {
            "segmentId": "m66442:caption:fig-ch03_04_03-caption"
          },
          "media": {
            "id": "fs-id2626112",
            "alt": "The formation of a peptide bond between two amino acids is shown. When the peptide bond forms, the carbon from the carbonyl group becomes attached to the nitrogen from the amino group. The upper O upper H from the carboxyl group and an upper H from the amino group form a molecule of water.",
            "src": "../../media/Figure_03_04_03.jpg",
            "mimeType": "image/jpg"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "para",
          "id": "fs-id1415197",
          "segmentId": "m66442:para:fs-id1415197"
        },
